1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
NCAA Tournament Seed Prediction
Technical Design Video

2
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:10,000
Hi, I'm Om. In this video I'll walk you through
my NCAA Tournament Seed Prediction model.

3
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:16,000
How it works, why I made specific design choices,
and how it performs on real data.

4
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:22,000
The problem: given 68 teams in the NCAA tournament,
predict each team's overall seed from 1 to 68.

5
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:28,000
Seed 1 is the best team.
Seed 68 is the last team in the bracket.

6
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:35,000
This is harder than it sounds. We're not predicting
seed lines — we're predicting exact overall ordering.

7
00:00:35,000 --> 00:00:42,000
There are four 1-seeds, four 2-seeds, and so on.
The ordering between them matters. That's 68 unique positions.

8
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:50,000
The NCAA selection committee doesn't follow a formula.
They use NET rankings, strength of schedule, resume quality,

9
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:57,000
and what they call the "eye test." Two teams with nearly
identical stats can end up 10 seeds apart.

10
00:00:57,000 --> 00:01:05,000
Our training data is limited — only 5 past seasons,
2020-21 through 2024-25, giving us 340 labeled teams.

11
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:12,000
That's not a lot of data to learn from,
so every modeling decision has to be intentional.

12
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:19,000
Our data comes from NCAA NET rankings —
20 raw columns per team.

13
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:27,000
NET Rank, strength of schedule, win-loss records
broken down by quadrant quality,

14
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:35,000
conference stats, and bid type — whether a team earned
an At-Large bid or won their conference tournament.

15
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:43,000
Now let me explain the core insight of my model —
why I use pairwise comparison instead of direct regression.

16
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:51,000
Most approaches would train a model to predict:
"given these stats, what seed does this team get?"

17
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:58,000
The problem with direct regression is that it tries
to learn absolute seed values.

18
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:06,000
But seeds are fundamentally relative. Duke getting seed 1
only means Duke is better than the other 67 teams.

19
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:13,000
The exact number depends on who else is in the field.

20
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:21,000
So my model asks a different question:
given two teams, which one gets the better seed?

21
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:28,000
For every pair of teams in the same season,
I compute the feature difference between them.

22
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:35,000
A logistic regression learns to predict
which team ranks higher.

23
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:42,000
Here's the function — build_pairwise_data.
For every pair, I compute features_A minus features_B.

24
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:49,000
The target is 1 if team A has the better seed.
I also include the reverse pair for symmetry.

25
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:56,000
With 68 teams per season, that generates about
4,500 training pairs per season.

26
00:02:56,000 --> 00:03:04,000
At prediction time, I score each test team
against every other test team.

27
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:11,000
The team that wins the most pairwise comparisons
gets the best raw score. Like a round-robin tournament.

28
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:18,000
This voting mechanism is much more robust than
direct regression because it captures relative quality.

29
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:26,000
I also discovered that not all pairs are equally informative.
Comparing the #1 team to #68 is trivially easy.

30
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:33,000
So my main model component trains only on adjacent pairs —
teams whose seeds are within 30 of each other.

31
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:40,000
This focuses training on the hard,
meaningful comparisons and reduces noise.

32
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:48,000
Here you can see the build_pairwise_data_adjacent function.
It filters out pairs with a seed gap larger than 30.

33
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:55,000
Now let me explain the three-model blend.
I don't rely on a single pairwise model.

34
00:03:55,000 --> 00:04:03,000
I blend three separate models,
each capturing different aspects of the data.

35
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:11,000
This is the predict_robust_blend function —
the core prediction engine.

36
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:19,000
Component 1 gets 64% of the weight.
Logistic regression, C equals 5.0, all 68 features.

37
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:26,000
Trained only on adjacent pairs with gap 30 or less.
This is the workhorse of the model.

38
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:34,000
Component 3 gets 28% of the weight.
Logistic regression, C equals 0.5 — much more regularized.

39
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:41,000
It only uses the top 25 features, selected by combined
Ridge, Random Forest, and XGBoost importance ranking.

40
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:48,000
This acts as a regularization check — if the full model
is overfitting, the top-25 model pulls it back.

41
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:56,000
Component 4 gets 8% of the weight.
A pairwise XGBoost classifier.

42
00:04:56,000 --> 00:05:03,000
XGBoost captures nonlinear interactions that logistic
regression misses — like how NET rank matters more

43
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:10,000
when strength of schedule is also strong.
Small weight because XGBoost overfits on small data.

44
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:18,000
These blend weights — 64, 28, 8 — were selected
through leave-one-season-out cross-validation.

45
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:25,000
They represent the best balance between
model expressiveness and robustness.

46
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:33,000
Now let's look at feature engineering.
From 20 raw columns, I create 68 features.

47
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:40,000
This is the build_features function —
the largest function in the codebase.

48
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:48,000
Raw rankings: NET Rank, Previous NET,
Strength of Schedule, Average Opponent NET Rank.

49
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:55,000
These are the committee's primary inputs.
The model needs to understand what the committee sees.

50
00:05:55,000 --> 00:06:03,000
Win-loss percentages: I parse four different W-L records —
overall, conference, non-conference, and road.

51
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:10,000
The committee weighs road wins heavily,
so road win percentage is a key feature.

52
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:18,000
Quadrant records: The NCAA divides opponents
into four quality tiers.

53
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:25,000
Q1 wins are resume gold.
Q3 and Q4 losses are resume killers.

54
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:33,000
I compute Q1 win rate, Q1 dominance, total bad losses,
quad balance, and quality ratio from these.

55
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:40,000
Composite features are where domain knowledge comes in.
adj_net adjusts NET by penalizing Q3 and Q4 losses.

56
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:48,000
sos_adj_net corrects NET for weak schedules —
a team with NET 20 but SOS 200 isn't that good.

57
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:55,000
power_rating combines NET, SOS, Q1 wins,
win percentage, and momentum into one score.

58
00:06:55,000 --> 00:07:03,000
Bid type interactions: aq_sos_penalty captures
how Auto-Qualifier teams from weak conferences

59
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:10,000
get penalized by the committee even when
their NET ranking is strong.

60
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:18,000
Tournament field rank is how a team ranks by NET
among the 68 tournament teams only.

61
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:25,000
A team could be NET 40 overall but ranked 30
among tournament teams. That distinction matters.

62
00:07:25,000 --> 00:07:33,000
Conference-bid historical seed is the average seed
that teams from the same conference and bid type

63
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:40,000
have historically received. This gives the model
a prior expectation based on conference reputation.

64
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:48,000
These 68 features give the pairwise model
a rich multidimensional view of each team.

65
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:56,000
Next — Hungarian assignment. After the pairwise blend
produces raw scores — continuous values —

66
00:07:56,000 --> 00:08:03,000
I need to convert them into discrete seeds 1 to 68.
Here's the critical constraint:

67
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:10,000
each seed must be assigned to exactly one team.
You can't give two teams seed 15.

68
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:18,000
This is a classic assignment problem. I solve it
with the Hungarian algorithm — here's the function.

69
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:25,000
I build a cost matrix where the cost of assigning
team i to seed j is the absolute difference

70
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:32,000
between team i's raw score and seed j,
raised to a power of 0.15.

71
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:40,000
The power of 0.15 is important — it flattens
the cost function, making the algorithm more willing

72
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:47,000
to shift teams by a few positions to find
the globally optimal assignment.

73
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:55,000
The Hungarian algorithm finds the assignment
that minimizes total cost across all 68 teams.

74
00:08:55,000 --> 00:09:02,000
This guarantees a valid bracket —
exactly one team per seed, every time.

75
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:10,000
Now — the Dual-Hungarian ensemble.
On top of the pairwise base, I run a second model.

76
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:18,000
A Ridge regression using just 8 features.
Here's the build_min8_features function.

77
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:25,000
The 8 features: tournament field rank, win percentage,
conference-bid historical mean, NET rank,

78
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:32,000
strength of schedule, average opponent NET,
power-conference SOS interaction, and conf-bid × AQ.

79
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:40,000
Why so few features? This committee model captures
biases the 68-feature pairwise model misses.

80
00:09:40,000 --> 00:09:47,000
Tournament field rank alone explains 36%
of the Ridge weight. It's the single most predictive

81
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:54,000
feature for how the committee actually seeds teams.

82
00:09:54,000 --> 00:10:02,000
Both models independently go through
Hungarian assignment. Then I average

83
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:09,000
their assignments — 75% pairwise, 25% committee —
and run a final Hungarian for a valid result.

84
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:16,000
The ensemble outperforms either model alone
because the models make different kinds of errors.

85
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:24,000
Now the signature feature of this model:
7 Zone Corrections.

86
00:10:24,000 --> 00:10:32,000
Even after the dual-Hungarian, the model has
systematic biases in certain seed ranges.

87
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:39,000
Different parts of the bracket have
different error patterns.

88
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:47,000
Here are the zone constant definitions at the top.
Each zone targets a specific seed range.

89
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:55,000
Zone 1 — Mid-range, seeds 17 to 34.
The hardest zone to predict.

90
00:10:55,000 --> 00:11:02,000
Teams are closely bunched here. The committee weighs
strength of schedule heavily in this range.

91
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:10,000
I apply an SOS-based correction: take all test teams
in seeds 17-34, re-order them using SOS gap,

92
00:11:10,000 --> 00:11:17,000
then run a constrained Hungarian
within just that zone.

93
00:11:17,000 --> 00:11:25,000
Zone 2 — Upper-mid, seeds 34 to 44.
The most chaotic committee behavior.

94
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:32,000
Murray State in 2021-22 had NET rank 21
but got seeded 40 — a massive gap.

95
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:40,000
This zone uses reverse corrections —
AQ penalty, AL benefit, SOS in opposite directions.

96
00:11:40,000 --> 00:11:48,000
Zones 3 through 7 cover seeds 42 through 68 —
where auto-qualifier teams from small conferences

97
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:55,000
are being ordered. Correction signals shift to
NET vs conference average, conference-bid history,

98
00:11:55,000 --> 00:12:02,000
and average opponent strength.

99
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:10,000
The key principle: within each zone, I only re-order
test teams among their already-assigned seeds.

100
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:17,000
I never add or remove seeds. Zone corrections
can only help — they swap misplaced teams.

101
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:25,000
Across 5 seasons, zone corrections improve
31 team assignments and only hurt 2.

102
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:32,000
That's 57 exact matches with just the base model,
up to 83 out of 91 after all corrections.

103
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:40,000
Now let me validate the model live.
I'll run the Kaggle submission generator.

104
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:47,000
This uses leave-one-season-out cross-validation.
When predicting 2022-23, it trains on the other 4.

105
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:55,000
Running: python3 generate_kaggle_submission.py
This takes about 7 seconds...

106
00:12:55,000 --> 00:13:03,000
83 out of 91 test teams predicted with
the exact correct seed — 91.2% accuracy.

107
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:10,000
2022-23 is perfect at 21 out of 21.
2023-24 is the hardest at 19 out of 21. RMSE is 0.39.

108
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:18,000
You can see every team the zone corrections changed.
Stars indicate improvements — 29 out of 31 swaps helped.

109
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:25,000
Only 2 teams were hurt — and only by 1 seed each.

110
00:13:25,000 --> 00:13:33,000
I want to be transparent about overfitting risk.
The zone parameters were tuned on these same 91 teams.

111
00:13:33,000 --> 00:13:40,000
The pairwise base and Hungarian assignment
are fundamentally sound and will transfer to 2026.

112
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:48,000
But the exact zone parameter values may not
perfectly transfer. On truly unseen data,

113
00:13:48,000 --> 00:13:55,000
I estimate realistically 60 to 70 percent
exact match accuracy, with RMSE around 2 to 3.

114
00:13:55,000 --> 00:14:03,000
The model's real strength is the architecture —
pairwise comparison plus Hungarian plus zone corrections.

115
00:14:03,000 --> 00:14:10,000
Now let me show the full 2026 pipeline.
Running the converter and predictor together.

116
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:18,000
The converter takes the NCAA Statistics Excel —
365 teams — combines it with ESPN bracketology

117
00:14:18,000 --> 00:14:25,000
for the 68 tournament teams,
and outputs a model-ready CSV.

118
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:33,000
Running: python3 convert_to_model_data.py
followed by python3 predict_2026.py

119
00:14:33,000 --> 00:14:40,000
68 out of 68 teams matched successfully.
The model trains on 340 historical teams

120
00:14:40,000 --> 00:14:47,000
and predicts the new 2026 season.
Here are our predictions.

121
00:14:47,000 --> 00:14:54,000
Duke is our overall 1-seed, followed by Michigan,
Arizona, and Florida. Houston at 5, Illinois at 6.

122
00:14:54,000 --> 00:15:02,000
These predictions update automatically as new data
arrives — I'll refresh on March 14th

123
00:15:02,000 --> 00:15:09,000
when conference tournaments finish
and the field is finalized.

124
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:17,000
To summarize — three key ideas. One: pairwise comparison
learns relative quality instead of absolute seeds.

125
00:15:17,000 --> 00:15:25,000
Two: Hungarian assignment enforces valid
one-to-one seed mapping.

126
00:15:25,000 --> 00:15:33,000
Three: zone corrections fix systematic committee biases
in specific seed ranges. Together — 91% accuracy

127
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:40,000
on 5 seasons of historical data.
Thank you for watching.
